class Solution {
public:
    int removeDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {

        int j = 0;

        for (int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++) {

            if (nums[i] != nums[j]) {
                j++;
                nums[j] = nums[i];
            }
        }

        return j + 1;
    }
};


Interview Explanation (30 seconds)

"Since the array is sorted, duplicates always appear next to each other. I use two pointers: i scans every element, while j keeps track of the last unique element. Whenever nums[i] is different from nums[j], I increment j and copy the new unique value to nums[j]. At the end, the first j + 1 elements contain all unique values."

Complexity
Time: O(n) (one pass)
Space: O(1) (in-place)
🧠 Pattern to Remember

This is the classic slow and fast pointer pattern:

Fast pointer (i) → Reads every element.
Slow pointer (j) → Marks where the next valid (unique) element should be placed.
